            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Vikram Malhotra\u2019s story is one of adaptation. Born to a family of academics in Delhi, he grew up surrounded by books and spirited debate, developing a fascination for the stories hidden within everyday life. This passion led him to the United States in the late 1980s to pursue a journalism degree at UC Berkeley. He fell in love with San Francisco's rebellious spirit and literary history, feeling he had found his true home.\n\nHis early career was the stuff of his dreams, working as a features writer for a prominent San Francisco newspaper. He thrived on the energy of the newsroom, the thrill of the deadline, and the satisfaction of seeing his byline in print. He married another writer, and for a decade, they lived a life rich in culture and experience, if not in wealth.\n\nThe key turning point came with the dot-com bust of the early 2000s, which decimated the newspaper industry. After being laid off, Vikram faced a stark choice: leave the city he loved or pivot. Pragmatism won. He leveraged his skills in storytelling and editing to land a role in corporate communications at a burgeoning tech company. Over two decades, he climbed the ladder to his current position as a Managing Editor, overseeing a team that produces technical documentation and informational content. The work is stable and lucrative, but it lacks the soul of his former profession. The marriage, strained by financial pressures and divergent career paths, ended amicably a few years later.\n\nToday, Vikram lives a quiet, ordered life in Cole Valley. His daily routine is anchored by his commute on the N-Judah streetcar, a 5.1-mile journey where he reads fiction, reclaiming a piece of the literary world he left behind. He is a familiar face at his local coffee shop and enjoys walks through Golden Gate Park. His relationship with his daughter, Anjali, now a junior at UCLA, is his greatest source of pride. He sees his own youthful idealism reflected in her.\n\nVikram is content, but a quiet aspiration smolders beneath the surface. He dreams of one day leaving the world of corporate-sanitized prose to write a novel\u2014a story about the changing face of San Francisco, as seen through the eyes of an immigrant who has witnessed it all."
